    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-01-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-01-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="762"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d762">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_LUCECB1">Luce</persName> files, lot 64 F 26, “Washington
                    Trip—January 1, 1954”</note>
                <head>No. 762<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Summary of Conference, by the Chief of the Military Assistance
                        Advisory Group in Italy (<persName corresp="#p_CHRISTIANSENJG1"
                            >Christiansen</persName>)</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d762fn1">
                        <p>A longer, more detailed memorandum of this conference, drafted by Ripps
                            of <gloss target="#t_FOA1">FOA</gloss>, with a full list of
                            participants, is in Italian Desk files, lot 57 D 56, “435—Aid to
                            Italy”.</p>
                        <p>The source text was one of two attachments to a memorandum of Jan. 14,
                            1954, from <persName corresp="#p_CHRISTIANSENJG1"
                                >Christiansen</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_LUCECB1"
                                >Luce</persName>, in which <persName corresp="#p_CHRISTIANSENJG1"
                                >Christiansen</persName> stated, “I attach two Secret papers that
                            contain information concerning your Washington trip.” The other
                            attachment was another memorandum from <persName
                                corresp="#p_CHRISTIANSENJG1">Christiansen</persName> to <persName
                                corresp="#p_LUCECB1">Luce</persName>, also dated Jan. 14, which
                                <persName corresp="#p_CHRISTIANSENJG1">Christiansen</persName>
                            explained he had made for the record since its substance did not appear
                            in any other record known to him. He noted, “After the meeting with
                            Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName> on 2
                            January 1954, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_NASHFC1">Nash</persName>,
                            Assistant Secretary of Defense, asked General <persName
                                corresp="#p_CHRISTIANSENJG1">Christiansen</persName> if a slowdown
                            in delivery of <gloss target="#t_MDAP1">MDAP</gloss> equipment to Italy
                            was desired. General <persName corresp="#p_CHRISTIANSENJG1"
                                >Christiansen</persName> replied that a slowdown was not desired by
                            him at this time but that policy should be checked with the Ambassador.
                            Mr. <persName corresp="#p_NASHFC1">Nash</persName> then asked the
                            Ambassador the same question—her reply was that a slowdown was not
                            desired at this time.”</p>
                    </note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-01-05">January 5,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Principal Participants:</head>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_LUCECB1">Luce</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>AS Defense <persName corresp="#p_NASHFC1">Nash</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_VOORHEESTS1">Tracy Voorhees</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Maj Gen <persName corresp="#p_STEWARTGC1">Stewart</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_TASCAHJ1">Henry Tasca</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_FOA1">FOA</gloss>, Rome</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_FREUNDRB1">Freund</persName>, Office Sec
                        State</item>
                    <pb facs="0559" n="1649" xml:id="pg_1649"/>
                    <item>Maj Gen <persName corresp="#p_CHRISTIANSENJG1">Christiansen</persName>,
                            <gloss target="#t_MAAGIT1">MAAGIT</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Several other State Dept officials</item>
                </list>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_LUCECB1">Luce</persName> opened the meeting with
                    a brief statement and then called on Mr. <persName corresp="#p_TASCAHJ1"
                        >Tasca</persName>. After a short presentation by Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_TASCAHJ1">Tasca</persName> concerning Embassy desires on <gloss
                        target="#t_OSP1">OSP</gloss> a general discussion followed. Main points made
                    were: <list>
                        <label>a.</label>
                        <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_VOORHEESTS1">Voorhees</persName>—about 200
                            million will probably be available for <gloss target="#t_OSP1"
                                >OSP</gloss>. This is exclusive of money available for F86 K
                            program. General <persName corresp="#p_STEWARTGC1">Stewart</persName>
                            suggested using figure smaller than 200 million. Final agreement was to
                            effect that Ambassador in approaching the Italian government should use
                            100 to 150 million figure instead of 200.</item>
                        <label>b.</label>
                        <item>
                            <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_NASHFC1">Nash</persName> and Mr. <persName
                                    corresp="#p_VOORHEESTS1">Voorhees</persName> both approve using
                                the possibility of reduction or cancellation of <gloss
                                    target="#t_OSP1">OSP</gloss> orders to secure political pressure
                                to help reduce the communist threat. Mr. <persName
                                    corresp="#p_NASHFC1">Nash</persName> adding that continued
                                pressure was necessary not just a “one-shot” deal.</p>
                            <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                        </item>
                        <label>d.</label>
                        <item>The F 86 K program<note n="2" xml:id="d762fn2">The Department of
                                Defense had been considering since the summer of 1953 the question
                                of placing orders for all-weather F–86 K fighters with <gloss
                                    target="#t_Fiat1">Fiat</gloss> in addition to the contract let
                                in May 1953 for the assembly by <gloss target="#t_Fiat1"
                                    >Fiat</gloss> of 50 F–86 K fighters. Background information on
                                this subject was provided in a memorandum for the files by <persName
                                    corresp="#p_LEVYHAWESMG1">Levy-Hawes</persName>, Dec. 11.
                                (Italian Desk files, lot 57 D 56, “435.03 <gloss target="#t_OSP1"
                                    >OSP</gloss> (Jan.–March ’54)”)</note> was outlined by Mr.
                                <persName corresp="#p_VOORHEESTS1">Voorhees</persName> as follows:
                            The Ambassador and others agree that the assembly of the original 50
                            should go ahead because to stop now after so much negotiating and
                            talking had been done would be inadvisable. The need for approximately
                            62 more such planes would be taken care of as follows: Contract with
                            North American Aviation to produce the pieces but fix the assembly phase
                            so that it could be decided later whether to offer further assembly job
                            to <gloss target="#t_Fiat1">Fiat</gloss> or to North American.… Mr.
                                <persName corresp="#p_NASHFC1">Nash</persName> said he would
                            telephone Mr. <persName corresp="#p_VALLETTAV1">Valletta</persName>’s
                            representative that <persName corresp="#p_VALLETTAV1"
                                >Valletta</persName> should stay in Italy until after Ambassador had
                            talked to him. The question of whether the 37.5 million available for
                            production of aircraft in Italy would be used for the 62 additional was
                            not clearly developed.</item>
                        <label>e.</label>
                        <item>
                            <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_VOORHEESTS1">Voorhees</persName>. The 200
                                million possible for <gloss target="#t_OSP1">OSP</gloss> is of
                                course dependent on proper prices being proposed by Italian
                                contractors.</p>
                            <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>J.A.C.</persName>
                    </signed>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d762fn3">A typewritten notation after the initials reads:
                        “This summary made by General <persName corresp="#p_CHRISTIANSENJG1"
                            >Christiansen</persName> and checked by Mr. <persName
                            corresp="#p_TASCAHJ1">Tasca</persName>.”</note>
                </closer>
            </div>
